The objective for this EAGER supported research project was to assess the current I-Corps program in terms of diversity, equity, and inclusive innovation (D,E, &amp;I).  We interacted with more than 70 faculty innovators, program managers and past-participants in the I-Corps program through this research includng and a June 2021 I-Corps Stakeholers meeting.  Findings from this research identified challenges in several aspects of the I-Corps program.  These challenges permeate all aspects of the I-Corps program and present significant obstacles to creating a welcoming and supportive environment that is inclusive of women and Under-Represented Minorities (URMs). We identified the following findings from the interviewing and interacting with key stakeholders:  1) Diversity initiatives are happening in several sites and nodes but they are not well-diffused and/or disseminated. 2)  There is no clearinghouse for commonly used materials by the teaching teams.  3) Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion is deliberate/intentional. It does not happen automatically.  4) Partnerships can work when attempting to increase diversity and inclusion. 5) Tailoring the program to the cultural values of the participants can attract more diverse teams to I-Corps. 6) The Relentlessly Direct Method of Instruction is not particularly productive with URMs-especially so for women URMs. 7) Diversity in the instructor and mentor pool leads to better participants outcomes and experiences.8) Pre-I-Corps training/programs (or on-ramps) are useful for women and URMs to prepare them for the culture shock of I-Corps.

After reviewing the findings we made six recommendations for improving D,E, &amp; I in I-Corps.   These recommendations to NSF have the potential to make I-Corps more relevant and responsive to the emerging community of diverse innovators.  The six recommendations from the final report are below.  

Establish common metrics for measuring diversity, equity and inclusion;
Audit I-Corps nodes/hubs and sites for diversity practices and outcomes;
Encourage diverse teaching teams;
Develop instructor team training that address bias and helps instructors develop inclusive teaching practices;
Cultivate partnerships and collaborations that will lead to more diverse participants (i.e. NSF ADVANCE, GEM i4);
Diffuse best practices throughout the national innovation network (NIN).


